# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: one-way-functions
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:one-way-functions/computational-indistinguishability] In computational complexity and cryptography, two families of distributions are **computationally indistinguishable** if no efficient algorithm can tell the difference between them except with negligible probability.
[src:one-way-functions/computational-indistinguishability] In other words, every efficient algorithm *A'*s behavior does not significantly change when given samples according to *D**n* or *E**n* in the limit as $n\to \infty$ .
[src:one-way-functions/computational-indistinguishability] Another interpretation of computational indistinguishability is that polynomial-time algorithms actively trying to distinguish between the two ensembles cannot do so: that any such algorithm will only perform negligibly better than if one were to just guess.
[src:one-way-functions/computational-indistinguishability] Implicit in the definition is the condition that the algorithm, A , must decide based on a single sample from one of the distributions.
[src:one-way-functions/computational-indistinguishability] One might conceive of a situation in which the algorithm trying to distinguish between two distributions, could access as many samples as it needed.
[src:one-way-functions/computational-indistinguishability] Hence two ensembles that cannot be distinguished by polynomial-time algorithms looking at multiple samples are deemed **indistinguishable by polynomial-time sampling**.
[src:one-way-functions/computational-indistinguishability] If the polynomial-time algorithm can generate samples in polynomial time, or has access to a random oracle that generates samples for it, then indistinguishability by polynomial-time sampling is equivalent to computational indistinguishability.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashing is a one-directional mathematical operation which is quick to calculate, yet hard to reverse.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] So password storage and digital signatures benefit from hashes.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Even a small change in the input results in a very different hash.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] So it is useful to check if two copies of data or software match.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Typically the operation works on a block of input data; the hash output is then hashed with the next block, creating a new hash reflecting everything to that point; again and again until the final hash reflects everything through the final block.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Cryptographic hash functions have many information-security applications, notably in digital signatures, message authentication codes (MACs), and other forms of authentication.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] They can also be used as ordinary hash functions, to index data in hash tables, for fingerprinting, to detect duplicate data or uniquely identify files, and as checksums to detect accidental data corruption.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Indeed, in information-security contexts, cryptographic hash values are sometimes called (*digital*) *fingerprints*, *checksums*, (*message*) *digests*, or just *hash values*, even though all these terms stand for more general functions with rather different properties and purposes.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic hash functions are used in hash tables and to detect accidental errors; their constructions frequently provide no resistance to a deliberate attack.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a denial-of-service attack on hash tables is possible if the collisions are easy to find, as in the case of linear cyclic redundancy check (CRC) functions.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Most cryptographic hash functions are designed to take a string of any length as input and produce a fixed-length hash value.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] A cryptographic hash function must be able to withstand all known types of cryptanalytic attack.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance implies second pre-image resistance but does not imply pre-image resistance.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The weaker assumption is always preferred in theoretical cryptography, but in practice, a hash-function that is only second pre-image resistant is considered insecure and is therefore not recommended for real applications.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Informally, these properties mean that a malicious adversary cannot replace or modify the input data without changing its digest.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Thus, if two strings have the same digest, one can be very confident that they are identical.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Second pre-image resistance prevents an attacker from crafting a document with the same hash as a document the attacker cannot control.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance prevents an attacker from creating two distinct documents with the same hash.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] A function meeting these criteria may still have undesirable properties.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Currently, popular cryptographic hash functions are vulnerable to *length-extension* attacks: given hash(*m*) and len(*m*) but not *m*, by choosing a suitable *m*′ an attacker can calculate hash(*m* ∥ *m*′), where ∥ denotes concatenation.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] This property can be used to break naive authentication schemes based on hash functions.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The HMAC construction works around these problems.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] In practice, collision resistance is insufficient for many practical uses.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] In addition to collision resistance, it should be impossible for an adversary to find two messages with substantially similar digests; or to infer any useful information about the data, given only its digest.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, a hash function should behave as much as possible like a random function (often called a random oracle in proofs of security) while still being deterministic and efficiently computable.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] This rules out functions like the SWIFFT function, which can be rigorously proven to be collision-resistant assuming that certain problems on ideal lattices are computationally difficult, but, as a linear function, does not satisfy these additional properties.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Checksum algorithms, such as CRC-32 and other cyclic redundancy checks, are designed to meet much weaker requirements and are generally unsuitable as cryptographic hash functions.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a CRC was used for message integrity in the WEP encryption standard, but an attack was readily discovered, which exploited the linearity of the checksum.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] In cryptographic practice, "difficult" generally means "almost certainly beyond the reach of any adversary who must be prevented from breaking the system for as long as the security of the system is deemed important".
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The meaning of the term is therefore somewhat dependent on the application since the effort that a malicious agent may put into the task is usually proportional to their expected gain.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] However, since the needed effort usually multiplies with the digest length, even a thousand-fold advantage in processing power can be neutralized by adding a dozen bits to the latter.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] For messages selected from a limited set of messages, for example passwords or other short messages, it can be feasible to invert a hash by trying all possible messages in the set.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Because cryptographic hash functions are typically designed to be computed quickly, special key derivation functions that require greater computing resources have been developed that make such brute-force attacks more difficult.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] In some theoretical analyses "difficult" has a specific mathematical meaning, such as "not solvable in asymptotic polynomial time".
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Such interpretations of *difficulty* are important in the study of provably secure cryptographic hash functions but do not usually have a strong connection to practical security.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, an exponential-time algorithm can sometimes still be fast enough to make a feasible attack.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Conversely, a polynomial-time algorithm (e.g., one that requires *n*20 steps for *n*-digit keys) may be too slow for any practical use.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] An illustration of the potential use of a cryptographic hash is as follows: Alice poses a tough math problem to Bob and claims that she has solved it.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Bob would like to try it himself, but would yet like to be sure that Alice is not bluffing.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Therefore, Alice writes down her solution, computes its hash, and tells Bob the hash value (whilst keeping the solution secret).
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Then, when Bob comes up with the solution himself a few days later, Alice can prove that she had the solution earlier by revealing it and having Bob hash it and then check that it matches the hash value given to him before.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] An important application of secure hashes is the verification of message integrity.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Comparing message digests (hash digests over the message) calculated before, and after, transmission can determine whether any changes have been made to the message or file.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5, SHA-1, or SHA-2 hash digests are sometimes published on websites or forums to allow verification of integrity for downloaded files, including files retrieved using file sharing such as mirroring.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] This practice establishes a chain of trust as long as the hashes are posted on a trusted site – usually the originating site – authenticated by HTTPS.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Using a cryptographic hash and a chain of trust detects malicious changes to the file.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic error-detecting codes such as cyclic redundancy checks only prevent against *non-malicious* alterations of the file, since an intentional spoof can readily be crafted to have the colliding code value.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Almost all digital signature schemes require a cryptographic hash to be calculated over the message.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] This allows the signature calculation to be performed on the relatively small, statically sized hash digest.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The message is considered authentic if the signature verification succeeds given the signature and recalculated hash digest over the message.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] So the message integrity property of the cryptographic hash is used to create secure and efficient digital signature schemes.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Password verification commonly relies on cryptographic hashes.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Storing all user passwords as cleartext can result in a massive security breach if the password file is compromised.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] One way to reduce this danger is to only store the hash digest of each password.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] To authenticate a user, the password presented by the user is hashed and compared with the stored hash.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] A password reset method is required when password hashing is performed; original passwords cannot be recalculated from the stored hash value.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] However, use of standard cryptographic hash functions, such as the SHA series, is no longer considered safe for password storage.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] These algorithms are designed to be computed quickly, so if the hashed values are compromised, it is possible to try guessed passwords at high rates.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Common graphics processing units can try billions of possible passwords each second.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Password hash functions that perform key stretching – such as PBKDF2, scrypt or Argon2 – commonly use repeated invocations of a cryptographic hash to increase the time (and in some cases computer memory) required to perform brute-force attacks on stored password hash digests.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] For details, see § Attacks on hashed passwords.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] A password hash also requires the use of a large random, non-secret salt value that can be stored with the password hash.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The salt is hashed with the password, altering the password hash mapping for each password, thereby making it infeasible for an adversary to store tables of precomputed hash values to which the password hash digest can be compared or to test a large number of purloined hash values in parallel.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] A proof-of-work system (or protocol, or function) is an economic measure to deter denial-of-service attacks and other service abuses such as spam on a network by requiring some work from the service requester, usually meaning processing time by a computer.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] A key feature of these schemes is their asymmetry: the work must be moderately hard (but feasible) on the requester side but easy to check for the service provider.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] One popular system – used in Bitcoin mining and Hashcash – uses partial hash inversions to prove that work was done, to unlock a mining reward in Bitcoin, and as a good-will token to send an e-mail in Hashcash.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender is required to find a message whose hash value begins with a number of zero bits.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The average work that the sender needs to perform in order to find a valid message is exponential in the number of zero bits required in the hash value, while the recipient can verify the validity of the message by executing a single hash function.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in Hashcash, a sender is asked to generate a header whose 160-bit SHA-1 hash value has the first 20 bits as zeros.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender will, on average, have to try 219 times to find a valid header.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] A message digest can also serve as a means of reliably identifying a file; several source code management systems, including Git, Mercurial and Monotone, use the sha1sum of various types of content (file content, directory trees, ancestry information, etc.) to uniquely identify them.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashes are used to identify files on peer-to-peer filesharing networks.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, in an ed2k link, an MD4-variant hash is combined with the file size, providing sufficient information for locating file sources, downloading the file, and verifying its contents.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Such file hashes are often the top hash of a hash list or a hash tree, which allows for additional benefits.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] One of the main applications of a hash function is to allow the fast look-up of data in a hash table.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Being hash functions of a particular kind, cryptographic hash functions lend themselves well to this application too.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] However, compared with standard hash functions, cryptographic hash functions tend to be much more expensive computationally.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage (CAS), also referred to as content-addressed storage or fixed-content storage, is a way to store information so it can be retrieved based on its content, not its name or location.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] It has been used for high-speed storage and retrieval of fixed content, such as documents stored for compliance with government regulations.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage is similar to content-addressable memory.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS systems work by passing the content of the file through a cryptographic hash function to generate a unique key, the "content address".
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The file system's directory stores these addresses and a pointer to the physical storage of the content.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Because an attempt to store the same file will generate the same key, CAS systems ensure that the files within them are unique, and because changing the file will result in a new key, CAS systems provide assurance that the file is unchanged.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS became a significant market during the 2000s, especially after the introduction of the 2002 Sarbanes–Oxley Act in the United States which required the storage of enormous numbers of documents for long periods and retrieved only rarely.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Ever-increasing performance of traditional file systems and new software systems have eroded the value of legacy CAS systems, which have become increasingly rare after roughly 2018.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] However, the principles of content addressability continue to be of great interest to computer scientists, and form the core of numerous emerging technologies, such as peer-to-peer file sharing, cryptocurrencies, and distributed computing.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] There are several methods to use a block cipher to build a cryptographic hash function, specifically a one-way compression function.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The methods resemble the block cipher modes of operation usually used for encryption.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Many well-known hash functions, including MD4, MD5, SHA-1 and SHA-2, are built from block-cipher-like components designed for the purpose, with feedback to ensure that the resulting function is not invertible.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 finalists included functions with block-cipher-like components (e.g., Skein, BLAKE) though the function finally selected, Keccak, was built on a cryptographic sponge instead.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] A standard block cipher such as AES can be used in place of these custom block ciphers; that might be useful when an embedded system needs to implement both encryption and hashing with minimal code size or hardware area.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] However, that approach can have costs in efficiency and security.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The ciphers in hash functions are built for hashing: they use large keys and blocks, can efficiently change keys every block, and have been designed and vetted for resistance to related-key attacks.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] General-purpose ciphers tend to have different design goals.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, AES has key and block sizes that make it nontrivial to use to generate long hash values; AES encryption becomes less efficient when the key changes each block; and related-key attacks make it potentially less secure for use in a hash function than for encryption.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function must be able to process an arbitrary-length message into a fixed-length output.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] This can be achieved by breaking the input up into a series of equally sized blocks, and operating on them in sequence using a one-way compression function.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The compression function can either be specially designed for hashing or be built from a block cipher.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function built with the Merkle–Damgård construction is as resistant to collisions as is its compression function; any collision for the full hash function can be traced back to a collision in the compression function.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The last block processed should also be unambiguously length padded; this is crucial to the security of this construction.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] This construction is called the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Most common classical hash functions, including SHA-1 and MD5, take this form.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] A straightforward application of the Merkle–Damgård construction, where the size of hash output is equal to the internal state size (between each compression step), results in a **narrow-pipe** hash design.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] This design causes many inherent flaws, including length-extension, multicollisions, long message attacks, generate-and-paste attacks, and also cannot be parallelized.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] As a result, modern hash functions are built on **wide-pipe** constructions that have a larger internal state size – which range from tweaks of the Merkle–Damgård construction to new constructions such as the sponge construction and HAIFA construction.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] None of the entrants in the NIST hash function competition use a classical Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Meanwhile, truncating the output of a longer hash, such as used in SHA-512/256, also defeats many of these attacks.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Hash functions can be used to build other cryptographic primitives.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] For these other primitives to be cryptographically secure, care must be taken to build them correctly.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Message authentication codes (MACs) (also called keyed hash functions) are often built from hash functions.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Just as block ciphers can be used to build hash functions, hash functions can be used to build block ciphers.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Luby-Rackoff constructions using hash functions can be provably secure if the underlying hash function is secure.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Also, many hash functions (including SHA-1 and SHA-2) are built by using a special-purpose block cipher in a Davies–Meyer or other construction.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] That cipher can also be used in a conventional mode of operation, without the same security guarantees; for example, SHACAL, BEAR and LION.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Pseudorandom number generators (PRNGs) can be built using hash functions.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] This is done by combining a (secret) random seed with a counter and hashing it.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Some hash functions, such as Skein, Keccak, and RadioGatún, output an arbitrarily long stream and can be used as a stream cipher, and stream ciphers can also be built from fixed-length digest hash functions.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Often this is done by first building a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator and then using its stream of random bytes as keystream.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is a stream cipher that uses SHA-1 to generate internal tables, which are then used in a keystream generator more or less unrelated to the hash algorithm.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is not guaranteed to be as strong (or weak) as SHA-1.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Similarly, the key expansion of the HC-128 and HC-256 stream ciphers makes heavy use of the SHA-256 hash function.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Concatenating outputs from multiple hash functions provide collision resistance as good as the strongest of the algorithms included in the concatenated result.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, older versions of Transport Layer Security (TLS) and Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) used concatenated MD5 and SHA-1 sums.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] This ensures that a method to find collisions in one of the hash functions does not defeat data protected by both hash functions.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] For Merkle–Damgård construction hash functions, the concatenated function is as collision-resistant as its strongest component, but not more collision-resistant.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Antoine Joux observed that 2-collisions lead to *n*-collisions: if it is feasible for an attacker to find two messages with the same MD5 hash, then they can find as many additional messages with that same MD5 hash as they desire, with no greater difficulty.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Among those *n* messages with the same MD5 hash, there is likely to be a collision in SHA-1.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The additional work needed to find the SHA-1 collision (beyond the exponential birthday search) requires only polynomial time.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] There are many cryptographic hash algorithms; this section lists a few algorithms that are referenced relatively often.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] A more extensive list can be found on the page containing a comparison of cryptographic hash functions.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 was designed by Ronald Rivest in 1991 to replace an earlier hash function, MD4, and was specified in 1992 as RFC 1321.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against MD5 can be calculated within seconds, which makes the algorithm unsuitable for most use cases where a cryptographic hash is required.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 produces a digest of 128 bits (16 bytes).
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The original specification – now commonly called SHA-0 – of the algorithm was published in 1993 under the title Secure Hash Standard, FIPS PUB 180, by U.S. government standards agency NIST (National Institute of Standards and Technology).
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] It was withdrawn by the NSA shortly after publication and was superseded by the revised version, published in 1995 in FIPS PUB 180-1 and commonly designated SHA-1.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against the full SHA-1 algorithm can be produced using the shattered attack and the hash function should be considered broken.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-1 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Documents may refer to SHA-1 as just "SHA", even though this may conflict with the other Secure Hash Algorithms such as SHA-0, SHA-2, and SHA-3.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD (RACE Integrity Primitives Evaluation Message Digest) is a family of cryptographic hash functions developed in Leuven, Belgium, by Hans Dobbertin, Antoon Bosselaers, and Bart Preneel at the COSIC research group at the Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, and first published in 1996.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD was based upon the design principles used in MD4 and is similar in performance to the more popular SHA-1.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD-160 has, however, not been broken.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] As the name implies, RIPEMD-160 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is a cryptographic hash function designed by Vincent Rijmen and Paulo S.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Barreto, who first described it in 2000.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is based on a substantially modified version of the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES).
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool produces a hash digest of 512 bits (64 bytes).
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 (Secure Hash Algorithm 2) is a set of cryptographic hash functions designed by the United States National Security Agency (NSA), first published in 2001.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] They are built using the Merkle–Damgård structure, from a one-way compression function itself built using the Davies–Meyer structure from a (classified) specialized block cipher.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 basically consists of two hash algorithms: SHA-256 and SHA-512.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-224 is a variant of SHA-256 with different starting values and truncated output.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-512 is more secure than SHA-256 and is commonly faster than SHA-256 on 64-bit machines such as AMD64.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The output size in bits is given by the extension to the "SHA" name, so SHA-224 has an output size of 224 bits (28 bytes); SHA-256, 32 bytes; SHA-384, 48 bytes; and SHA-512, 64 bytes.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 (Secure Hash Algorithm 3) was released by NIST on August 5, 2015.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 is a subset of the broader cryptographic primitive family Keccak.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The Keccak algorithm is the work of Guido Bertoni, Joan Daemen, Michael Peeters, and Gilles Van Assche.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Keccak is based on a sponge construction, which can also be used to build other cryptographic primitives such as a stream cipher.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 provides the same output sizes as SHA-2: 224, 256, 384, and 512 bits.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Configurable output sizes can also be obtained using the SHAKE-128 and SHAKE-256 functions.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Here the -128 and -256 extensions to the name imply the security strength of the function rather than the output size in bits.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE2, an improved version of BLAKE, was announced on December 21, 2012.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn, and Christian Winnerlein with the goal of replacing the widely used but broken MD5 and SHA-1 algorithms.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] When run on 64-bit x64 and ARM architectures, BLAKE2b is faster than SHA-3, SHA-2, SHA-1, and MD5.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Although BLAKE and BLAKE2 have not been standardized as SHA-3 has, BLAKE2 has been used in many protocols including the Argon2 password hash, for the high efficiency that it offers on modern CPUs.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] As BLAKE was a candidate for SHA-3, BLAKE and BLAKE2 both offer the same output sizes as SHA-3 – including a configurable output size.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3, an improved version of BLAKE2, was announced on January 9, 2020.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jack O'Connor, Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, and Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3 is a single algorithm, in contrast to BLAKE and BLAKE2, which are algorithm families with multiple variants.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The BLAKE3 compression function is closely based on that of BLAKE2s, with the biggest difference being that the number of rounds is reduced from 10 to 7.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Internally, BLAKE3 is a Merkle tree, and it supports higher degrees of parallelism than BLAKE2.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] There is a long list of cryptographic hash functions but many have been found to be vulnerable and should not be used.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Even if a hash function has never been broken, a successful attack against a weakened variant may undermine the experts' confidence.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in August 2004 collisions were found in several then-popular hash functions, including MD5.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] These weaknesses called into question the security of stronger algorithms derived from the weak hash functions – in particular, SHA-1 (a strengthened version of SHA-0), RIPEMD-128, and RIPEMD-160 (both strengthened versions of RIPEMD).
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] On August 12, 2004, Joux, Carribault, Lemuel, and Jalby announced a collision for the full SHA-0 algorithm.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Joux et al. accomplished this using a generalization of the Chabaud and Joux attack.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] They found that the collision had complexity 251 and took about 80,000 CPU hours on a supercomputer with 256 Itanium 2 processors – equivalent to 13 days of full-time use of the supercomputer.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] In February 2005, an attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collision in about 269 hashing operations, rather than the 280 expected for a 160-bit hash function.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] In August 2005, another attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collisions in 263 operations.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Other theoretical weaknesses of SHA-1 have been known, and in February 2017 Google announced a collision in SHA-1.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Security researchers recommend that new applications can avoid these problems by using later members of the SHA family, such as SHA-2, or using techniques such as randomized hashing that do not require collision resistance.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] A successful, practical attack broke MD5 (used within certificates for Transport Layer Security) in 2008.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Many cryptographic hashes are based on the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] All cryptographic hashes that directly use the full output of a Merkle–Damgård construction are vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] This makes the MD5, SHA-1, RIPEMD-160, Whirlpool, and the SHA-256 / SHA-512 hash algorithms all vulnerable to this specific attack.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3, BLAKE2, BLAKE3, and the truncated SHA-2 variants are not vulnerable to this type of attack.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Rather than store plain user passwords, controlled-access systems frequently store the hash of each user's password in a file or database.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] When someone requests access, the password they submit is hashed and compared with the stored value.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] If the database is stolen (an all-too-frequent occurrence), the thief will only have the hash values, not the passwords.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Passwords may still be retrieved by an attacker from the hashes, because most people choose passwords in predictable ways.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Lists of common passwords are widely circulated and many passwords are short enough that even all possible combinations may be tested if calculation of the hash does not take too much time.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The use of cryptographic salt prevents some attacks, such as building files of precomputing hash values, e.g. rainbow tables.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] But searches on the order of 100 billion tests per second are possible with high-end graphics processors, making direct attacks possible even with salt.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] The United States National Institute of Standards and Technology recommends storing passwords using special hashes called key derivation functions (KDFs) that have been created to slow brute force searches.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] Slow hashes include pbkdf2, bcrypt, scrypt, argon2, Balloon and some recent modes of Unix crypt.
[src:one-way-functions/cryptographic-hash-function] For KDFs that perform multiple hashes to slow execution, NIST recommends an iteration count of 10,000 or more.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] In cryptography, a **hard-core predicate** of a one-way function *f* is a predicate *b* (i.e., a function whose output is a single bit) which is easy to compute (as a function of *x*) but is hard to compute given *f(x)*.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] In formal terms, there is no probabilistic polynomial-time (PPT) algorithm that computes *b(x)* from *f(x)* with probability significantly greater than one half over random choice of *x*.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] In other words, if *x* is drawn uniformly at random, then given *f(x)*, any PPT adversary can only distinguish the hard-core bit *b(x)* and a uniformly random bit with negligible advantage over the length of *x*.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] A **hard-core function** can be defined similarly.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] That is, if *x* is chosen uniformly at random, then given *f(x)*, any PPT algorithm can only distinguish the hard-core function value *h(x)* and uniformly random bits of length *|h(x)|* with negligible advantage over the length of *x*.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] A hard-core predicate captures "in a concentrated sense" the hardness of inverting *f*.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] While a one-way function is hard to invert, there are no guarantees about the feasibility of computing partial information about the preimage *c* from the image *f(x)*.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] For instance, while RSA is conjectured to be a one-way function, the Jacobi symbol of the preimage can be easily computed from that of the image.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] It is clear that if an injective function has a hard-core predicate, then it must be a one-way function.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] Oded Goldreich and Leonid Levin (1989) showed how every one-way function can be trivially modified to obtain a one-way function that has a specific hard-core predicate.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] Define *g(x,r) = (f(x), r)* where the length of *r* is the same as that of *x*.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] Let *xj* denote the *j*th bit of *x* and *rj* the *j*th bit of *r*.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] Note that *b(x, r)* = <*x, r*> where <·, ·> denotes the standard inner product on the vector space (**Z**2)*n*.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] This predicate is hard-core due to computational issues; that is, it is not hard to compute because *g(x, r)* is information theoretically lossy.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] Rather, if there exists an algorithm that computes this predicate efficiently, then there is another algorithm that can invert *f* efficiently.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] A similar construction yields a hard-core function with *O(log |x|)* output bits.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] Suppose *f* is a strong one-way function.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] Choose a length function *l(n)* = *O(log n)* s.t.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] It is sometimes the case that an actual bit of the input *x* is hard-core.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] For example, every single bit of inputs to the RSA function is a hard-core predicate of RSA and blocks of *O(log |x|)* bits of *x* are indistinguishable from random bit strings in polynomial time (under the assumption that the RSA function is hard to invert).
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] Hard-core predicates give a way to construct a pseudorandom generator from any one-way permutation.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] is a pseudorandom bit sequence, where *fn* means the n-th iteration of applying *f* on *s*, and *b* is the generated hard-core bit by each round *n*.
[src:one-way-functions/hard-core-predicate] Hard-core predicates of trapdoor one-way permutations (known as **trapdoor predicates**) can be used to construct semantically secure public-key encryption schemes.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] In computer science, a **one-way function** is a function that is easy to compute on every input, but hard to invert given the image of a random input.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Here, "easy" and "hard" are to be understood in the sense of computational complexity theory, specifically the theory of polynomial time problems.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] This has nothing to do with whether the function is one-to-one; finding any one input with the desired image is considered a successful inversion.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] The existence of such one-way functions is still an open conjecture.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Their existence would prove that the complexity classes P and NP are not equal, thus resolving the foremost unsolved question of theoretical computer science.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] The converse is not known to be true, i.e. the existence of a proof that P ≠ NP would not directly imply the existence of one-way functions.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] In applied contexts, the terms "easy" and "hard" are usually interpreted relative to some specific computing entity; typically "cheap enough for the legitimate users" and "prohibitively expensive for any malicious agents".
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] One-way functions, in this sense, are fundamental tools for cryptography, personal identification, authentication, and other data security applications.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] While the existence of one-way functions in this sense is also an open conjecture, there are several candidates that have withstood decades of intense scrutiny.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Some of them are essential ingredients of most telecommunications, e-commerce, and e-banking systems around the world.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] A function *f* : {0, 1}* → {0, 1}* is **one-way** if *f* can be computed by a polynomial-time algorithm, but any polynomial-time randomized algorithm F that attempts to compute a pseudo-inverse for *f* succeeds with negligible probability.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] where the probability is over the choice of *x* from the discrete uniform distribution on {0, 1} *n*, and the randomness of F .
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Note that, by this definition, the function must be "hard to invert" in the average-case, rather than worst-case sense.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] This is different from much of complexity theory (e.g., NP-hardness), where the term "hard" is meant in the worst-case.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] That is why even if some candidates for one-way functions (described below) are known to be NP-complete, it does not imply their one-wayness.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] The latter property is only based on the lack of known algorithms to solve the problem.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] It is not sufficient to make a function "lossy" (not one-to-one) to have a one-way function.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] In particular, the function that outputs the string of *n* zeros on any input of length *n* is *not* a one-way function because it is easy to come up with an input that will result in the same output.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] More precisely: For such a function that simply outputs a string of zeroes, an algorithm *F* that just outputs any string of length *n* on input *f*(*x*) will "find" a proper preimage of the output, even if it is not the input which was originally used to find the output string.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] A **one-way permutation** is a one-way function that is also a permutation—that is, a one-way function that is bijective.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] One-way permutations are an important cryptographic primitive, and it is not known if their existence is implied by the existence of one-way functions.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] A trapdoor one-way function or trapdoor permutation is a special kind of one-way function.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Such a function is hard to invert unless some secret information, called the *trapdoor*, is known.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] A **collision-free hash function** *f* is a one-way function that is also *collision-resistant*; that is, no randomized polynomial time algorithm can find a collision—distinct values *x*, *y* such that *f*(*x*) = *f*(*y*)—with non-negligible probability.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] A hard-core predicate of a one-way function *f* is a predicate (i.e. single bit) *b* such that *b(x)* is easy to compute given *x* but hard to compute given only *f(x)*.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] If *f* is a one-way function, then the inversion of *f* would be a problem whose output is hard to compute (by definition) but easy to check (just by computing *f* on it).
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Thus, the existence of a one-way function implies that FP ≠ FNP, which in turn implies that P ≠ NP.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] However, P ≠ NP does not imply the existence of one-way functions.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] The following are several candidates for one-way functions (as of April 2009).
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Clearly, it is not known whether these functions are indeed one-way; but extensive research has so far failed to produce an efficient inverting algorithm for any of them.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] The function *f* takes as inputs two prime numbers *p* and *q* in binary notation and returns their product.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] This function can be "easily" computed in *O*(*b*2) time, where *b* is the total number of bits of the inputs.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Inverting this function requires finding the factors of a given integer *N*.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] The best factoring algorithms known run in $O\left(\exp {\sqrt[{3}]{{\frac {64}{9}}b(\log b)^{2}}}\right)$ time, where b is the number of bits needed to represent *N*.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] This function can be generalized by allowing *p* and *q* to range over a suitable set of semiprimes.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] The **Rabin function**, or squaring modulo $N=pq$ , where p and q are primes is believed to be a collection of one-way functions.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] to denote squaring modulo N: a specific member of the **Rabin collection**.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] It can be shown that extracting square roots, i.e. inverting the Rabin function, is computationally equivalent to factoring N (in the sense of polynomial-time reduction).
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Hence it can be proven that the Rabin collection is one-way if and only if factoring is hard.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] This also holds for the special case in which p and q are of the same bit length.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] The Rabin signature algorithm is based on the assumption that this Rabin function is one-way.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Modular exponentiation can be done in polynomial time.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Inverting this function requires computing the discrete logarithm.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Currently there are several popular groups for which no algorithm to calculate the underlying discrete logarithm in polynomial time is known.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] These groups are all finite abelian groups and the general discrete logarithm problem can be described as thus.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Let *G* be a finite abelian group of cardinality *n*.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Denote its group operation by multiplication.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Consider a primitive element *α* ∈ *G* and another element *β* ∈ *G*.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] The integer *k* that solves the equation *αk* = *β* is termed the **discrete logarithm** of *β* to the base *α*.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Popular choices for the group *G* in discrete logarithm cryptography are the cyclic groups (**Z***p*)*×* (e.g.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] ElGamal encryption, Diffie–Hellman key exchange, and the Digital Signature Algorithm) and cyclic subgroups of elliptic curves over finite fields (*see* elliptic curve cryptography).
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] An elliptic curve is a set of pairs of elements of a field satisfying *y*2 = *x*3 + *ax* + *b*.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] The elements of the curve form a group under an operation called "point addition" (which is not the same as the addition operation of the field).
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Multiplication *kP* of a point *P* by an integer *k* (*i.e.*, a group action of the additive group of the integers) is defined as repeated addition of the point to itself.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] If *k* and *P* are known, it is easy to compute *R* = *kP*, but if only *R* and *P* are known, it is assumed to be hard to compute *k*.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] There are a number of cryptographic hash functions that are fast to compute, such as SHA-256.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Some of the simpler versions have fallen to sophisticated analysis, but the strongest versions continue to offer fast, practical solutions for one-way computation.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Most of the theoretical support for the functions are more techniques for thwarting some of the previously successful attacks.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Other candidates for one-way functions include the hardness of the decoding of random linear codes, the hardness of certain lattice problems, and the subset sum problem (Naccache–Stern knapsack cryptosystem).
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] There is an explicit function *f* that has been proved to be one-way, if and only if one-way functions exist.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] In other words, if any function is one-way, then so is *f*.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Since this function was the first combinatorial complete one-way function to be demonstrated, it is known as the "universal one-way function".
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] The problem of finding a one-way function is thus reduced to proving—perhaps non-constructively—that one such function exists.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] There also exists a function that is one-way if polynomial-time bounded Kolmogorov complexity is mildly hard on average.
[src:one-way-functions/one-way-function] Since the existence of one-way functions implies that polynomial-time bounded Kolmogorov complexity is mildly hard on average, the function is a universal one-way function.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] The random seed itself is typically a short binary string drawn from the uniform distribution.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Many different classes of statistical tests have been considered in the literature, among them the class of all Boolean circuits of a given size.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] It is not known whether good pseudorandom generators for this class exist, but it is known that their existence is in a certain sense equivalent to (unproven) circuit lower bounds in computational complexity theory.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Hence the construction of pseudorandom generators for the class of Boolean circuits of a given size rests on currently unproven hardness assumptions.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] These functions are the *statistical tests* that the pseudorandom generator will try to fool, and they are usually algorithms.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Sometimes the statistical tests are also called *adversaries* or *distinguishers*.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] The notation in the codomain of the functions is the Kleene star.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] The quantity $\ell$ is called the *seed length* and the quantity $n-\ell$ is called the *stretch* of the pseudorandom generator.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] In most applications, the family ${\mathcal {A}}$ represents some model of computation or some set of algorithms, and one is interested in designing a pseudorandom generator with small seed length and bias, and such that the output of the generator can be computed by the same sort of algorithm.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] In cryptography, the class ${\mathcal {A}}$ usually consists of all circuits of size polynomial in the input and with a single bit output, and one is interested in designing pseudorandom generators that are computable by a polynomial-time algorithm and whose bias is negligible in the circuit size.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] These pseudorandom generators are sometimes called **cryptographically secure pseudorandom generators (CSPRGs)**.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] It is not known if cryptographically secure pseudorandom generators exist.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Proving that they exist is difficult since their existence implies P ≠ NP, which is widely believed but a famously open problem.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] The existence of cryptographically secure pseudorandom generators is widely believed.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] This is because it has been proven that pseudorandom generators can be constructed from any one-way function which are believed to exist.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Pseudorandom generators are necessary for many applications in cryptography.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] The pseudorandom generator theorem shows that cryptographically secure pseudorandom generators exist if and only if one-way functions exist.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Pseudorandom generators have numerous applications in cryptography.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] For instance, pseudorandom generators provide an efficient analog of one-time pads.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] It is well known that in order to encrypt a message *m* in a way that the cipher text provides no information on the plaintext, the key *k* used must be random over strings of length |m|.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Perfectly secure encryption is very costly in terms of key length.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Key length can be significantly reduced using a pseudorandom generator if perfect security is replaced by semantic security.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Common constructions of stream ciphers are based on pseudorandom generators.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Pseudorandom generators may also be used to construct symmetric key cryptosystems, where a large number of messages can be safely encrypted under the same key.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Such a construction can be based on a pseudorandom function family, which generalizes the notion of a pseudorandom generator.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Then in the 1990s, various idealizations of physics simulations—based on random walks, correlation functions, localization of eigenstates, etc., were used as tests of pseudorandom generators.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] NIST announced SP800-22 Randomness tests to test whether a pseudorandom generator produces high quality random bits.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Yongge Wang showed that NIST testing is not enough to detect weak pseudorandom generators and developed statistical distance based testing technique LILtest.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] A main application of pseudorandom generators lies in the derandomization of computation that relies on randomness, without corrupting the result of the computation.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Physical computers are deterministic machines, and obtaining true randomness can be a challenge.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Pseudorandom generators can be used to efficiently simulate randomized algorithms with using little or no randomness.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] In such applications, the class ${\mathcal {A}}$ describes the randomized algorithm or class of randomized algorithms that one wants to simulate, and the goal is to design an "efficiently computable" pseudorandom generator against ${\mathcal {A}}$ whose seed length is as short as possible.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] If a full derandomization is desired, a completely deterministic simulation proceeds by replacing the random input to the randomized algorithm with the pseudorandom string produced by the pseudorandom generator.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] The simulation does this for all possible seeds and averages the output of the various runs of the randomized algorithm in a suitable way.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] A fundamental question in computational complexity theory is whether all polynomial time randomized algorithms for decision problems can be deterministically simulated in polynomial time.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] The existence of such a simulation would imply that **BPP** = **P**.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] In 1991, Noam Nisan and Avi Wigderson provided a candidate pseudorandom generator with these properties.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] In 1997 Russell Impagliazzo and Avi Wigderson proved that the construction of Nisan and Wigderson is a pseudorandom generator assuming that there exists a decision problem that can be computed in time 2O(*n*) on inputs of length *n* but requires circuits of size 2Ω(*n*).
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] While unproven assumption about circuit complexity are needed to prove that the Nisan–Wigderson generator works for time-bounded machines, it is natural to restrict the class of statistical tests further such that we need not rely on such unproven assumptions.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] One class for which this has been done is the class of machines whose work space is bounded by $O(\log n)$ .
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Using a repeated squaring trick known as Savitch's theorem, it is easy to show that every probabilistic log-space computation can be simulated in space $O(\log ^{2}n)$ .
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Noam Nisan (1992) showed that this derandomization can actually be achieved with a pseudorandom generator of seed length $O(\log ^{2}n)$ that fools all $O(\log n)$ -space machines.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Nisan's generator has been used by Saks and Zhou (1999) to show that probabilistic log-space computation can be simulated deterministically in space $O(\log ^{1.5}n)$ .
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] This result was improved by William Hoza in 2021 to space $O(\log ^{1.5}n/{\sqrt {\log \log n}})$ .
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] When the statistical tests consist of all multivariate linear functions over some finite field $\mathbb {F}$ , one speaks of epsilon-biased generators.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] The construction of Naor & Naor (1990) achieves a seed length of $\ell =\log n+O(\log(\epsilon ^{-1}))$ , which is optimal up to constant factors.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Pseudorandom generators for linear functions often serve as a building block for more complicated pseudorandom generators.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Viola (2008) proves that taking the sum of d small-bias generators fools polynomials of degree d .
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Constant depth circuits that produce a single output bit.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] The pseudorandom generators used in cryptography and universal algorithmic derandomization have not been proven to exist, although their existence is widely believed.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Proofs for their existence would imply proofs of lower bounds on the circuit complexity of certain explicit functions.
[src:one-way-functions/pseudorandom-generator] Such circuit lower bounds cannot be proved in the framework of natural proofs assuming the existence of stronger variants of cryptographic pseudorandom generators.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] In theoretical computer science and cryptography, a **trapdoor function** is a function that is easy to compute in one direction, yet difficult to compute in the opposite direction (finding its inverse) without special information, called the "trapdoor".
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] Trapdoor functions are a special case of one-way functions and are widely used in public-key cryptography.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] In mathematical terms, if *f* is a trapdoor function, then there exists some secret information *t*, such that given *f*(*x*) and *t*, it is easy to compute *x*.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] It is trivial to change the padlock from open to closed without using the key, by pushing the shackle into the lock mechanism.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] Opening the padlock easily, however, requires the key to be used.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] Here the key *t* is the trapdoor and the padlock is the trapdoor function.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] An example of a simple mathematical trapdoor is "6895601 is the product of two prime numbers.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] What are those numbers?" A typical "brute-force" solution would be to try dividing 6895601 by many prime numbers until finding the answer.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] However, if one is told that 1931 is one of the numbers, one can find the answer by entering "6895601 ÷ 1931" into any calculator.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] This example is not a sturdy trapdoor function – modern computers can guess all of the possible answers within a second – but this sample problem could be improved by using the product of two much larger primes.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] Trapdoor functions came to prominence in cryptography in the mid-1970s with the publication of asymmetric (or public-key) encryption techniques by Diffie, Hellman, and Merkle.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] Indeed, Diffie & Hellman (1976) coined the term.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] Several function classes had been proposed, and it soon became obvious that trapdoor functions are harder to find than was initially thought.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] For example, an early suggestion was to use schemes based on the subset sum problem.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] This turned out rather quickly to be unsuitable.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] As of 2004, the best known trapdoor function (family) candidates are the RSA and Rabin families of functions.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] Both are written as exponentiation modulo a composite number, and both are related to the problem of prime factorization.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] A trapdoor in cryptography has the very specific aforementioned meaning and is not to be confused with a backdoor (these are frequently used interchangeably, which is incorrect).
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] A backdoor is a deliberate mechanism that is added to a cryptographic algorithm (e.g., a key pair generation algorithm, digital signing algorithm, etc.) or operating system, for example, that permits one or more unauthorized parties to bypass or subvert the security of the system in some fashion.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] If each function in the collection above is a one-way permutation, then the collection is also called a **trapdoor permutation**.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] In the following two examples, we always assume that it is difficult to factorize a large composite number (see Integer factorization).
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] If the factorization of $n=pq$ is known, then $\phi (n)=(p-1)(q-1)$ can be computed.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] With this the inverse d of e can be computed $d=e^{-1}\mod {\phi (n)}$ , and then given $y=f(x)$ , we can find $x=y^{d}\mod n=x^{ed}\mod n=x\mod n$ .
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] Its hardness follows from the RSA assumption.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] Let n be a large composite number such that $n=pq$ , where p and q are large primes such that $p\equiv 3{\pmod {4}},q\equiv 3{\pmod {4}}$ , and kept confidential to the adversary.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] The problem is to compute z given a such that $a\equiv z^{2}{\pmod {n}}$ .
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] The trapdoor is the factorization of n .
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] See Chinese remainder theorem for more details.
[src:one-way-functions/trapdoor-function] Here the conditions $p\equiv 3{\pmod {4}}$ and $q\equiv 3{\pmod {4}}$ guarantee that the solutions x and y can be well defined.
